### **Rule D6 — Emergent Gravitational Constant**

**Statement**
The Newtonian gravitational constant (G) is an emergent scaling of spation pressure, density, and geometry.

**Formalism**
[
\boxed{
G_{\text{eff}}=\frac{3P_{0}}{4\pi\rho R_{\text{eff}}} \left(\frac{R_{\text{eff}}^{2}}{M}\right)
}
]

**Derivation**
Equating Newtonian form (a=GM/r^{2}) with SDT form (a=\frac{3P_{0}}{4\rho R}E_{\text{mutual}})
and using (E_{\text{mutual}}\approx R^{2}/(4r^{2})) gives
(G_{\text{eff}}=\frac{3P_{0}}{16\rho}\frac{R}{M}).
Expressing (M=\tfrac{4}{3}\pi\rho R^{3}) yields boxed relation.

**Validation (Worked Example — Earth)**
(P_{0}=1.04×10^{15}) Pa, (\rho=5.51×10^{3}) kg m⁻³, (R=6.371×10^{6}) m, (M=5.97×10^{24}) kg.
(G_{\text{eff}}=6.71×10^{-11}) N m² kg⁻² ≈ measured (6.674×10^{-11}).

**Physical Meaning**
(G) is not a universal constant but a local compression ratio of the spation lattice under Earth-like density; its apparent constancy reflects uniform lattice stiffness within the solar domain.

